      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Originalism is a moral imperative because it forces judges to respect the democratic will of the people who wrote the Constitution, rather than allowing unelected judges to rewrite the law based on their own modern preferences. Proponents argue that the Constitution is a fixed contract that must be interpreted through the original understanding of its framers to ensure stability and prevent judicial overreach. By adhering to the text as it was originally understood, originalism protects minority rights by locking in the specific protections the Founders intended, rather than letting the majority impose new values on the past. Ultimately, this approach maintains the separation of powers and ensures that only the elected branches can change the fundamental law of the land.",
